</taxonomicName>
have been collected as larvae in the field and reared in the laboratory. For additional information see Comments for those species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="156" pageNumber="157" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="156.[151,1437,153,1835]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,801,827]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Etymology.</emphasis>
Probably 
<emphasis box="[450,518,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Gleno</emphasis>
- (from 
<taxonomicName box="[606,710,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[606,710,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an antlion genus-group name) + - 
<emphasis box="[1100,1148,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">leon</emphasis>
(from Greek leon, lion; a traditional antlion genus-group name ending), in allusion to the former generic placements and antlion taxonomic affinities of its originally included species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="156" pageNumber="157" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="156.[151,1437,153,1835]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,908,935]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Comments.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[461,578,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[461,578,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was created by 
<bibRefCitation author="Banks, N." box="[753,903,909,935]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="201 - 242" refId="ref216516" refString="Banks, N. (1913) Synopses and descriptions of exotic Neuroptera. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 39, 201 - 242." type="journal article" year="1913">Banks (1913)</bibRefCitation>
to hold the Australian species previously placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Schneider" authorityName="Schneider" box="[181,407,945,971]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[181,285,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenurus</emphasis>
Schneider
</taxonomicName>
, a phylogenetically distant genus now placed in Nemoleontinae: 
<taxonomicName authority="(Machado et al. 2019)" baseAuthorityName="Machado" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Glenurini">
Glenurini (
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Gillung, J. P. &amp; Winterton, S. L. &amp; Garzon-Orduna, I. J. &amp; Lemmon, A. R. &amp; Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D." pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="418 - 450" refId="ref217247" refString="Machado, R. J. P., Gillung, J. P., Winterton, S. L., Garzon-Orduna, I. J., Lemmon, A. R., Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D. (2019) Owlflies are derived antlions: anchored phylogenomics supports a new phylogeny and classification of Myrmeleontidae (Neuroptera). Systematic Entomology, 44, 418 - 450. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12334" type="journal article" year="2019">
Machado 
<emphasis box="[1379,1437,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Banks originally included six species in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[691,808,981,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[691,808,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and proposed several characters to define it, including: RP arising before CuA fork; forewing and hind wing with three and one presectoral crossveins respectively; hind wing anal vein not running parallel to CuP; anterior Banksian line present; legs slender and spurs long. However, most of these characters are widely present in many Australian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1899" box="[896,1066,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Dendroleontini">Dendroleontini</taxonomicName>
and it was subsequently recognized that the genus lacked strongly definitive characters. Shortly after Banksâ€™ initial paper, five new species were described in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[298,415,1161,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[298,415,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="New, T. R." box="[595,763,1160,1187]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="1 - 170" refId="ref217575" refString="New, T. R. (1985 b) A revision of the Australian Myrmeleontidae (Insecta: Neuroptera). II. Dendroleontini. Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series, 105, 1 - 170. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / AJZS 105" type="journal article" year="1985">Newâ€™s (1985b)</bibRefCitation>
revision of the group increased the size of the genus to 32 species (where it stood at the beginning of this study), but he (admittedly) made little headway in improving the phylogenetic definition of the group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="156.[151,1437,153,1835]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">
<bibRefCitation author="New, T. R." box="[199,346,1268,1295]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="1 - 170" refId="ref217575" refString="New, T. R. (1985 b) A revision of the Australian Myrmeleontidae (Insecta: Neuroptera). II. Dendroleontini. Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series, 105, 1 - 170. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / AJZS 105" type="journal article" year="1985">New (1985b)</bibRefCitation>
intentionally treated the genus very broadly and understood that the apparent superficial similarity of many species belied significant differences in male and female terminalic structure. However, as the patterns of terminalic variation were poorly understood, he chose to retain numerous species in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[1096,1213,1341,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1096,1213,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based primarily on the simple shared presence of tibial spurs. New noted that his circumscription of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[1075,1192,1377,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1075,1192,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was likely unnatural, and would eventually need to be reappraised and subdivided, probably based on terminalic traits. That idea was generally supported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stange, L. A." box="[374,535,1449,1475]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="1 - 565" refId="ref218011" refString="Stange, L. A. (2004) A systematic catalog, bibliography and classification of the world antlions (Insecta: Neuroptera: Myrmeleontidae). Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 74, [i-iv] + 1 - 565." type="journal article" year="2004">Stange (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, and the polyphyletic nature of the genus in its then-current form was confirmed by the phylogenomic analysis of 
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Gillung, J. P. &amp; Winterton, S. L. &amp; Garzon-Orduna, I. J. &amp; Lemmon, A. R. &amp; Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D." box="[525,779,1485,1511]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="418 - 450" refId="ref217247" refString="Machado, R. J. P., Gillung, J. P., Winterton, S. L., Garzon-Orduna, I. J., Lemmon, A. R., Lemmon, E. M. &amp; Oswald, J. D. (2019) Owlflies are derived antlions: anchored phylogenomics supports a new phylogeny and classification of Myrmeleontidae (Neuroptera). Systematic Entomology, 44, 418 - 450. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12334" type="journal article" year="2019">
Machado 
<emphasis box="[637,694,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
. After restudying all of its species for the current revision, and conducting an additional morphological phylogenetic analysis (
<figureCitation box="[931,1003,1521,1547]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,348,1348]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1436,345,1348]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 4. Strict consensus tree of morphology-based parsimony analysis of species belonging to the former subtribe Periclystina (ingroup, names in black), and outgroups (names in red). Former Glenoleon species are shown on blue branches, former Austrogymnocnemia species on green branches. Numbers above branches are Bremer support values; numbers below branches are bootstrap values (shown where&gt;50%)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3896822" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3896822/files/figure.png" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), the circumscription of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[1291,1408,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1291,1408,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is redefined here. Most of its former species are removed to other genera, some of which are new, and the genus is restricted to its 
<typeStatus box="[325,373,1593,1619]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">type</typeStatus>
species and five closest relatives.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="156.[151,1437,153,1835]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">
Among the species most closely related to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rambur" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[674,823,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Myrmeleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchellus">
<emphasis box="[674,823,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">G. pulchellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Esben-Petersen" baseAuthorityYear="1923" box="[854,985,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="froggatti">
<emphasis box="[854,985,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">G. froggatti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esben-Petersen" authorityYear="1923" box="[1322,1429,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Platyleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1322,1429,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Platyleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esben-Petersen" authorityYear="1923" box="[151,258,1665,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Platyleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,258,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Platyleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Esben-Petersen, P." box="[470,727,1665,1691]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="576 - 592" refId="ref216786" refString="Esben-Petersen, P. (1923) Australian Neuroptera. Part IV. Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales, 48, 576 - 592." type="journal article" year="1923">Esben-Petersen (1923)</bibRefCitation>
, who related it to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[935,1052,1665,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[935,1052,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Navas" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1914" box="[1108,1286,1665,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Mossega" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1108,1208,1666,1691]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Mossega</emphasis>
NavÃ¡s
</taxonomicName>
based on the large and biareolate costal area. The phylogenetic analyses, however, reveal those traits to be convergent, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Esben-Petersen" baseAuthorityYear="1923" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="froggatti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">G. froggatti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is nested well within the restricted concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[772,889,1737,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[772,889,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as sister to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rambur" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1021,1171,1737,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Myrmeleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchellus">
<emphasis box="[1021,1171,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">G. pulchellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="New" authorityYear="1985" box="[1226,1375,1737,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculatus">
<emphasis box="[1226,1375,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">G. maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,348,1348]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1436,345,1348]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 4. Strict consensus tree of morphology-based parsimony analysis of species belonging to the former subtribe Periclystina (ingroup, names in black), and outgroups (names in red). Former Glenoleon species are shown on blue branches, former Austrogymnocnemia species on green branches. Numbers above branches are Bremer support values; numbers below branches are bootstrap values (shown where&gt;50%)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3896822" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3896822/files/figure.png" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Based on this evidence, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esben-Petersen" authorityYear="1923" box="[455,562,1773,1799]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Platyleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[455,562,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Platyleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is synonymized here with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[859,976,1773,1799]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[859,976,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In its new circumscription the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1913" box="[151,268,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Glenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,268,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Glenoleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are united primarily on the basis of traits of the female terminalia.
</paragraph>
